WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.152 --> 00:00:04.360
FEMALE SPEAKER: Hi, everyone.

00:00:04.360 --> 00:00:05.300
Welcome to Talks at Google.

00:00:05.300 --> 00:00:07.360
Today it is my pleasure
to welcome Jim Butcher

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:09.827
for "The Aeronaut's Windlass."

00:00:09.827 --> 00:00:11.620
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.620 --> 00:00:12.730
Jim, welcome to Google.

00:00:12.730 --> 00:00:13.180
JIM BUTCHER: Thank
you very much.

00:00:13.180 --> 00:00:15.429
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank you
for us being your first tech

00:00:15.429 --> 00:00:18.720
stop ever, not bookstore.

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:21.760
Can you tell us about the book?

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:24.314
JIM BUTCHER: It's
a steampunk novel.

00:00:24.314 --> 00:00:25.730
When I first started
pitching it I

00:00:25.730 --> 00:00:30.467
tried to tell people that it's
sort of X-Men meets Hornblower.

00:00:30.467 --> 00:00:33.050
But then I decided that wasn't
steampunky enough, so from then

00:00:33.050 --> 00:00:35.133
on I said it's "League of
Extraordinary Gentlemen"

00:00:35.133 --> 00:00:36.780
meets Hornblower.

00:00:36.780 --> 00:00:39.030
It's set in a world where
the surface of the world

00:00:39.030 --> 00:00:40.738
is very dangerous,
and so everybody lives

00:00:40.738 --> 00:00:43.410
in these enormous
black obsidian spires

00:00:43.410 --> 00:00:46.540
that were built many,
many, many moons ago.

00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:50.260
And all contact between the
spires is done by airship.

00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:51.930
All diplomacy, all
trade, all everything

00:00:51.930 --> 00:00:55.590
is done by airship
from spire to spire.

00:00:55.590 --> 00:00:58.360
Two of the more powerful
spires in this world

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:01.820
are in the opening stages of
going to war with one another,

00:01:01.820 --> 00:01:03.670
and the monarch of
a local spire has

00:01:03.670 --> 00:01:06.510
decided that he needs
an action team to help

00:01:06.510 --> 00:01:08.760
better position his spire
before the war gets started.

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:11.740
So he goes out and
recruits a pirate

00:01:11.740 --> 00:01:13.640
and a princess and a wizard.

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:15.390
There's a checklist.

00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:17.660
[LAUGH] I don't
make up these rules.

00:01:21.130 --> 00:01:24.790
And a warrior and a girl
who can talk to cats.

00:01:24.790 --> 00:01:25.900
Plus her cat.

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:31.442
Although it's not really as much
her cat is as she's his human.

00:01:31.442 --> 00:01:33.900
He gets this group together
and sends them off on a mission

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:36.620
to find a traitor
within their own midst

00:01:36.620 --> 00:01:39.020
before something totally
horrible happens.

00:01:39.020 --> 00:01:42.920
And then totally horrible things
happen, and adventure ensues.

00:01:42.920 --> 00:01:45.560
That's the first book as
we get to meet these people

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:47.170
and see the kind
of world they're in

00:01:47.170 --> 00:01:50.000
and then throw them
into hideous danger

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.280
against horrible monsters
and evil opponents

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:57.750
and not-so-evil opponents.

00:01:57.750 --> 00:02:00.580
I had a whole lot
of fun writing it.

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:03.270
It's one of the things
I've had a better

00:02:03.270 --> 00:02:06.634
time writing than many
other projects I've done.

00:02:06.634 --> 00:02:08.550
Also, it's the longest
book I've ever written.

00:02:08.550 --> 00:02:11.310
It checked in at
over 200,000 words.

00:02:11.310 --> 00:02:15.570
It's a falling hazard to
children and small animals.

00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:17.516
If you get the book,
be careful with that.

00:02:17.516 --> 00:02:20.140
FEMALE SPEAKER: I'd love to know
what some of your inspirations

00:02:20.140 --> 00:02:21.180
were for it.

00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:23.790
It felt like this
hybrid between a world

00:02:23.790 --> 00:02:25.970
where there's magic,
much like Dresden Files,

00:02:25.970 --> 00:02:30.320
but it's also this sort of
nobility-based oligarchy

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:30.912
situation.

00:02:30.912 --> 00:02:32.120
JIM BUTCHER: Not "Star Wars."

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:33.761
Definitely not "Star Wars."

00:02:33.761 --> 00:02:34.677
FEMALE SPEAKER: Never.

00:02:37.629 --> 00:02:39.420
JIM BUTCHER: Really,
the heaviest influence

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:43.710
probably came from the
nautical hero novel.

00:02:43.710 --> 00:02:48.540
You start with Hornblower--
that was Forester,

00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:53.711
I believe-- and then
the Jack Aubrey books

00:02:53.711 --> 00:02:56.210
that were the ones that were
published in the '90s, the ones

00:02:56.210 --> 00:02:58.074
they made "Master and
Commander" off of.

00:02:58.074 --> 00:02:59.990
"Master and Commander"
was my background movie

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:01.490
for while I was
writing this series.

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:09.150
Those and then David Weber's
Honor Harrington books,

00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:11.320
which also came from
that same source,

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:13.470
was also partially
an inspiration.

00:03:13.470 --> 00:03:19.860
And, because my brain is
not working right now,

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:22.220
"20,000 Leagues Under the Sea."

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:25.315
That's my strongest direct
steampunk influence,

00:03:25.315 --> 00:03:27.440
although that was just
science fiction at the time.

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:29.720
They didn't know to
call it steampunk.

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:32.030
I actually don't think
it's a steampunk novel.

00:03:32.030 --> 00:03:34.607
I wanted to call
it a steam opera,

00:03:34.607 --> 00:03:36.440
because it's like space
opera, but it's not.

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:37.100
It's airships.

00:03:37.100 --> 00:03:39.035
And so I wanted to
call it steam opera.

00:03:39.035 --> 00:03:40.660
My editor was like
"Jim, you can't just

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:42.910
go inventing genres like that."

00:03:42.910 --> 00:03:45.950
And I was like "Oh."

00:03:45.950 --> 00:03:50.610
But maybe if the series
gets enough oomph,

00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:51.860
maybe there'll be a new genre.

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:52.590
That would be cool.

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:53.370
FEMALE SPEAKER: You
can be a pioneer.

00:03:53.370 --> 00:03:54.120
JIM BUTCHER: Yeah.

00:03:54.120 --> 00:03:55.700
Yeah.

00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:58.650
FEMALE SPEAKER: It's interesting
that you mentioned nautical.

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:02.320
They're in the air,
but it felt very naval.

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:04.477
Did you do a lot of
research into that?

00:04:04.477 --> 00:04:06.560
Having read the "Master
and Commander" and Horatio

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:08.601
Hornblower books, I felt
like I was reading that,

00:04:08.601 --> 00:04:11.419
but at the same time, they're
soaring through the air.

00:04:11.419 --> 00:04:13.460
JIM BUTCHER: I was doing
a whole lot of research,

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:15.760
and then I finally realized
that I was researching

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:17.649
the wrong place,
because I really

00:04:17.649 --> 00:04:22.280
need to be researching
ballooning and blimp

00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:27.280
stuff, the blimp stuff from
World War I especially,

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:31.230
to find out more things
about was going on.

00:04:31.230 --> 00:04:33.447
I did get into
nautical research.

00:04:33.447 --> 00:04:35.280
And let me tell you--
this is what I learned

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:36.910
about nautical research.

00:04:36.910 --> 00:04:41.590
There is a name for everything,
and it makes no sense at all.

00:04:41.590 --> 00:04:44.340
But you had to have a specific
name for every little rope

00:04:44.340 --> 00:04:46.400
and every little stay
where the rope was tied off

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:48.320
and anything the
rope was attached to.

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:50.740
They all had to have these
very specific names so that

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:52.350
in the middle of a
crisis situation,

00:04:52.350 --> 00:04:54.600
somebody who was an officer
could look at you and say,

00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:55.690
"You!

00:04:55.690 --> 00:04:57.630
Something something
the mizzen bowsprit!"

00:04:57.630 --> 00:04:59.620
And you would know
exactly what had

00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:03.760
to be done, because
otherwise you might all die.

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:07.950
It was a very, technical,
very focused language

00:05:07.950 --> 00:05:10.600
for when you were working
on one of these ships.

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:13.129
And if you didn't know
it, you were a threat

00:05:13.129 --> 00:05:14.670
to everybody else,
because you needed

00:05:14.670 --> 00:05:16.270
to be able to do everything.

00:05:18.890 --> 00:05:19.390
Yes.

00:05:19.390 --> 00:05:21.180
There was so much research.

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:23.129
And I still need to
do more, because it's

00:05:23.129 --> 00:05:25.170
going to get more involved
as the series goes on,

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:28.190
because that's what series
do, from everything I've seen.

00:05:31.026 --> 00:05:33.150
I'm actually going to have
to get down to San Diego

00:05:33.150 --> 00:05:35.700
and go hang out on the tall
ships that are in the harbor

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:38.490
there and ask a lot of questions
and write a lot of things down.

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:39.980
FEMALE SPEAKER: Sounds like
a terrible, terrible research

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:40.220
experience.

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:41.053
JIM BUTCHER: I know!

00:05:41.053 --> 00:05:42.287
It'll be so awful!

00:05:42.287 --> 00:05:44.370
FEMALE SPEAKER: Is it
easier, in a case like that,

00:05:44.370 --> 00:05:48.340
to then just use our real-world
terminology for that,

00:05:48.340 --> 00:05:51.850
or would you rather create
your own in this scenario?

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:55.020
JIM BUTCHER: I like to use
real-world terminology whenever

00:05:55.020 --> 00:05:57.770
I can, because when
I'm writing, I'm

00:05:57.770 --> 00:06:00.930
doing the absolute best I
can to make the language as

00:06:00.930 --> 00:06:03.610
transparent as possible, so
that when you're reading,

00:06:03.610 --> 00:06:05.280
you forget that
you're reading words,

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:07.363
and you're just watching
the movie that is playing

00:06:07.363 --> 00:06:09.090
on the screen in your head.

00:06:09.090 --> 00:06:12.050
I try and do everything I can to
keep my language from intruding

00:06:12.050 --> 00:06:16.720
on the story that's happening,
which is why, I think,

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:19.810
I write at about an eighth-grade
reading level, on average--

00:06:19.810 --> 00:06:21.870
because I don't want
the words to get

00:06:21.870 --> 00:06:25.320
in the way of the
experience for the reader.

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:27.520
Books, I think, are the
first virtual reality.

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:31.480
And I invest very heavily
in that idea in the way

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:34.141
I've put together
my writing style.

00:06:34.141 --> 00:06:36.140
FEMALE SPEAKER: What's
something about this book

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:39.420
that you learned from
your previous series

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:41.850
that you enjoy being able
to explore in this series?

00:06:41.850 --> 00:06:43.605
What limitations
were removed for you

00:06:43.605 --> 00:06:44.813
from getting to start afresh?

00:06:48.609 --> 00:06:50.650
JIM BUTCHER: The Alera
books were the other books

00:06:50.650 --> 00:06:52.840
that I wrote before this,
and they were, similarly,

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:55.460
third-person, multiple
viewpoint characters.

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:59.800
And the pace for those
books was a little bit slow,

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:02.140
because they happened over
a broader span of time,

00:07:02.140 --> 00:07:06.466
for the most part, then when
compared to the Dresden Files.

00:07:06.466 --> 00:07:08.340
When I write the Dresden
Files, basically I'm

00:07:08.340 --> 00:07:12.586
writing about Harry Dresden's
worst weekend of the year.

00:07:12.586 --> 00:07:13.960
And so all the
story that happens

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:16.090
has to happen in this very
little compressed space.

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:18.256
I decided I wanted to try
and do that with this book

00:07:18.256 --> 00:07:21.970
as well, only from multiple
character viewpoints.

00:07:21.970 --> 00:07:24.690
The events of the story happen
in that same compressed space,

00:07:24.690 --> 00:07:26.856
but we see it from several
different points of view.

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:32.930
When you've got that,
then the question

00:07:32.930 --> 00:07:35.150
becomes where do
I put the camera

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:36.520
for this particular scene?

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:38.490
Which character is
best going to show you

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:40.352
know the events of this action?

00:07:40.352 --> 00:07:42.560
Which character is best
going to be involved in them?

00:07:42.560 --> 00:07:44.966
Which is the one that's
going to help the reader best

00:07:44.966 --> 00:07:46.090
understand what's going on?

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:48.465
Because I'll know what's going
on in this airship battle,

00:07:48.465 --> 00:07:51.390
but if I just write paragraphs
and paragraphs of airship

00:07:51.390 --> 00:07:53.770
battle, the reader
isn't necessarily

00:07:53.770 --> 00:07:55.020
going to know what's going on.

00:07:55.020 --> 00:07:56.400
So it's like OK, for
this fight, we're

00:07:56.400 --> 00:07:58.566
going to go over to this
character, who's never been

00:07:58.566 --> 00:08:00.240
on an airship
before, and yet who

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:03.072
is bossy enough
to demand answers

00:08:03.072 --> 00:08:05.030
to questions from people
who have better things

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:09.060
to be doing so that the reader
will get what's going on,

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:11.930
because the characters who
know will be explaining it

00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:13.920
to this dummy.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:17.640
It's a concept called the joy
of idiocy in writing craft.

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:20.050
You always keep an idiot
around to ask questions

00:08:20.050 --> 00:08:23.790
as a surrogate for the reader,
so that-- hopefully-- the idiot

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:25.990
asks the questions that
the reader wants answered,

00:08:25.990 --> 00:08:28.400
and then the reader gets to know
the answers without ever having

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:29.691
to admit that they didn't know.

00:08:32.409 --> 00:08:33.998
That's one of the
fun things you get

00:08:33.998 --> 00:08:36.039
to play with when you've
got multiple viewpoints.

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:37.300
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank
you for providing us all

00:08:37.300 --> 00:08:38.535
with very interesting idiots.

00:08:41.780 --> 00:08:43.860
As you said, it was a
great, awesome experience

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:44.960
to have these
multiple viewpoints.

00:08:44.960 --> 00:08:46.680
And one thing I loved
about this particular book

00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:48.890
is that you have a bunch
of wonderful women in it.

00:08:48.890 --> 00:08:51.880
It's, I think, at least
an even match-up of female

00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:54.480
protagonists to male, and
there's this whole range

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:56.804
on both genders.

00:08:56.804 --> 00:08:58.220
Where were some
of the inspiration

00:08:58.220 --> 00:09:00.580
for those characters?

00:09:00.580 --> 00:09:02.010
JIM BUTCHER: Some of them?

00:09:02.010 --> 00:09:06.390
I was writing, and
there they were.

00:09:06.390 --> 00:09:10.540
Bridget certainly
emerged that way.

00:09:10.540 --> 00:09:12.300
Gwen was a character
who actually

00:09:12.300 --> 00:09:14.590
emerged from a roleplaying
game that I was

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:15.780
running in this story world.

00:09:15.780 --> 00:09:18.145
That's how I do my research
for my story worlds.

00:09:18.145 --> 00:09:19.770
I'll get something
built, and then I'll

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:23.090
run a roleplaying
game in the world.

00:09:23.090 --> 00:09:25.670
That's always wonderful,
because when I do that,

00:09:25.670 --> 00:09:29.006
the players can never
do anything right.

00:09:29.006 --> 00:09:30.380
You can write any
script you want

00:09:30.380 --> 00:09:32.870
for the players-- they aren't
going to follow that script.

00:09:32.870 --> 00:09:34.840
They're going to
break it somehow.

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:37.120
And then you find you
find yourself frantically

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:39.820
building the world six
inches in front of their feet

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:43.240
as they are stopping off in
the completely wrong direction.

00:09:43.240 --> 00:09:44.760
It's a good exercise
in creativity,

00:09:44.760 --> 00:09:49.910
and it really helps me flesh
out things as I'm going along.

00:09:49.910 --> 00:09:51.580
She came from one
of the players.

00:09:57.850 --> 00:09:59.900
I knew what I wanted
my villain to be like.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:02.135
I knew I wanted my villain
to be evil Mary Poppins.

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:06.530
And she kind of is.

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:09.490
She's this very proper
person, and she can't kill you

00:10:09.490 --> 00:10:12.379
as long as you're being polite.

00:10:12.379 --> 00:10:14.670
But she just waits for you
to make a slip in etiquette,

00:10:14.670 --> 00:10:17.754
and then she can
tear your eyes out.

00:10:17.754 --> 00:10:18.795
A little bit of pressure.

00:10:18.795 --> 00:10:21.000
FEMALE SPEAKER: It's every
Catholic schoolchild's worst

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:21.499
nightmare.

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:26.860
There's one very unique
character who I very much

00:10:26.860 --> 00:10:28.535
enjoyed, and that is Rowl.

00:10:28.535 --> 00:10:30.730
You wrote a cat who talks.

00:10:30.730 --> 00:10:33.620
You wrote people
who talk to cats.

00:10:33.620 --> 00:10:34.445
What up with that?

00:10:36.740 --> 00:10:38.990
JIM BUTCHER: I wanted cats,
and I wanted talking cats.

00:10:38.990 --> 00:10:43.080
And I was thinking I
wanted to establish

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:44.660
this race of
intelligent cats that

00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:47.300
live alongside humanity,
not with humanity

00:10:47.300 --> 00:10:50.240
in a pet situation, because
that wouldn't really

00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:51.280
happen very well.

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:53.090
FEMALE SPEAKER: It's sort of a
pet situation in the other way.

00:10:53.090 --> 00:10:54.180
JIM BUTCHER: Yes.

00:10:54.180 --> 00:10:55.740
More it works the
other way around.

00:10:55.740 --> 00:10:58.730
These cats live alongside the
societies in these spires,

00:10:58.730 --> 00:11:01.490
and they live in the
vents and air tunnels

00:11:01.490 --> 00:11:05.217
and kill things that come in
there from the surface that

00:11:05.217 --> 00:11:05.800
are cat-sized.

00:11:09.954 --> 00:11:12.120
Humans don't really like
them, but they can't really

00:11:12.120 --> 00:11:13.661
get rid of them,
because they perform

00:11:13.661 --> 00:11:14.990
a really useful service.

00:11:14.990 --> 00:11:16.540
And they can't
really ignore them,

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:20.960
because the cats have
opposable thumbs and matches.

00:11:25.100 --> 00:11:27.920
So in a lot of
ways, for the cats,

00:11:27.920 --> 00:11:30.600
it's like oh, I notice your
warehouse is rodent-free.

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:34.100
Perhaps you would like it to
continue to be rodent-free.

00:11:34.100 --> 00:11:36.920
Perhaps there will be cream
waiting for us every Thursday

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:39.480
at 3:00.

00:11:39.480 --> 00:11:41.800
Really the cats are
this little fuzzy mafia

00:11:41.800 --> 00:11:47.360
that exists in an underworld
alongside humanity.

00:11:47.360 --> 00:11:50.490
But the cats also can go
everywhere and hear everything

00:11:50.490 --> 00:11:52.770
and learn everything,
because they're quiet,

00:11:52.770 --> 00:11:56.350
and they're smart, and
they have excellent senses.

00:11:56.350 --> 00:12:00.600
And the lord of the
spire, the spirarch,

00:12:00.600 --> 00:12:03.170
figures out that wait-- these
cats are really, really useful.

00:12:03.170 --> 00:12:06.396
We probably shouldn't just
treat them like vermin.

00:12:06.396 --> 00:12:07.770
I need every
advantage I can get.

00:12:07.770 --> 00:12:11.980
And so he recruits somebody
who's friends with a cat.

00:12:11.980 --> 00:12:15.620
Her father runs a vattery,
which is where they grow meat

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:18.806
in vats inside these spires.

00:12:18.806 --> 00:12:20.430
Basically, she works
in a butcher shop.

00:12:20.430 --> 00:12:22.160
They have a deal
with the local cats.

00:12:22.160 --> 00:12:24.243
She made friends with one
when she was very small.

00:12:24.243 --> 00:12:26.330
The cat named her Little Mouse.

00:12:26.330 --> 00:12:28.577
She's about six-two.

00:12:28.577 --> 00:12:30.410
The cat named her Little
Mouse, and then she

00:12:30.410 --> 00:12:33.380
grew up much larger than she
had been when he first met her,

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:36.244
which offended him greatly.

00:12:36.244 --> 00:12:37.160
He hangs out with her.

00:12:37.160 --> 00:12:40.190
So Rowl and Bridget are a team.

00:12:40.190 --> 00:12:42.060
Rowl taught Bridget
how to speak cat,

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:44.350
and so Bridget can
talk to the cats.

00:12:44.350 --> 00:12:47.775
The cats understand English,
except when they don't.

00:12:50.870 --> 00:12:53.070
They're the most obnoxious
little characters.

00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:54.990
Oh, my gosh!

00:12:54.990 --> 00:12:57.600
Honestly, I would like to
think these books will succeed

00:12:57.600 --> 00:12:59.680
because it's got
a cool story world

00:12:59.680 --> 00:13:01.430
or it's got really
identifiable characters

00:13:01.430 --> 00:13:02.920
or it's got great action
or because there's

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:03.960
good plots in them,
but they're going

00:13:03.960 --> 00:13:05.626
to succeed because
there's talking cats.

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:10.739
And I've made peace with that.

00:13:10.739 --> 00:13:13.030
FEMALE SPEAKER: Opposable
thumbs means signable checks.

00:13:13.030 --> 00:13:14.410
JIM BUTCHER: Yes, exactly.

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:16.785
The hard part is not letting
them steal the show from all

00:13:16.785 --> 00:13:18.144
the plain old boring humans.

00:13:18.144 --> 00:13:19.560
FEMALE SPEAKER: I
was so surprised

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:21.965
to learn that you were not
necessarily a cat person

00:13:21.965 --> 00:13:22.465
beforehand.

00:13:25.579 --> 00:13:27.120
I'm not a cat person,
but that's what

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:30.850
I imagine cats would sound
like in terms of [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:30.850 --> 00:13:32.600
JIM BUTCHER: I wasn't
a cat person myself.

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:35.980
But I knew cat people and
how they think and talk

00:13:35.980 --> 00:13:37.070
about their cats.

00:13:37.070 --> 00:13:39.280
I've been introduced
to cats for a long time

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:42.160
from the point of view of
those who love them very much.

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:43.832
Now I have cats.

00:13:43.832 --> 00:13:44.540
They're not mine.

00:13:44.540 --> 00:13:48.450
I got them for my fiancee, and
she named them after the cats

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:50.535
in the books.

00:13:50.535 --> 00:13:53.160
They're Maine coons, and they're
kittens, and they're enormous,

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:54.930
and they're adorable.

00:13:54.930 --> 00:13:56.000
I'm like go away, cat.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:57.964
I don't need to like you.

00:13:57.964 --> 00:13:58.630
Get out of here.

00:13:58.630 --> 00:13:59.963
We have a business relationship.

00:13:59.963 --> 00:14:00.880
Go.

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:03.690
And it's like why are you
sitting on my lap and purring?

00:14:03.690 --> 00:14:04.482
It's so adorable.

00:14:04.482 --> 00:14:04.982
Damn.

00:14:09.239 --> 00:14:11.280
FEMALE SPEAKER: You've
sort of touched upon this,

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:13.670
but you said you very much
enjoyed writing these books.

00:14:13.670 --> 00:14:17.680
What's something that was
different about writing them

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:21.490
from writing your other ones,
aside from talking cats?

00:14:21.490 --> 00:14:23.323
JIM BUTCHER: Right,
aside from talking cats.

00:14:25.860 --> 00:14:28.010
I was really working
on trying to make sure

00:14:28.010 --> 00:14:30.240
that I had down a
dialogue that didn't quite

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:33.670
sound like regular everyday--
the way people use their speech

00:14:33.670 --> 00:14:34.170
patterns.

00:14:34.170 --> 00:14:36.336
I was trying for something
a little bit more formal,

00:14:36.336 --> 00:14:38.670
a little bit more
archaic-sounding.

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:42.110
I wanted it to feel a little
bit more like "Downton Abby"

00:14:42.110 --> 00:14:44.120
without it actually
being that way.

00:14:48.010 --> 00:14:51.260
