00:32:16.130 --> 00:32:20.343
And she was talking about
the rest of the novel.

00:32:20.343 --> 00:32:22.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:22.750 --> 00:32:26.100
But I came running back into
conference the next week

00:32:26.100 --> 00:32:28.540
and was like OK, here--
I've got this planned out.

00:32:28.540 --> 00:32:29.290
I've got this whole
thing planned out.

00:32:29.290 --> 00:32:31.090
It's going to be about 20
books, maybe 21-- I'm not sure

00:32:31.090 --> 00:32:32.070
if I get them all
in in that time--

00:32:32.070 --> 00:32:33.490
and then there's going to be
a big old three-book trilogy

00:32:33.490 --> 00:32:35.020
at the end that kind of
capstones the entire thing.

00:32:35.020 --> 00:32:36.200
What do you think?

00:32:36.200 --> 00:32:39.010
And she just kind of
looks at me the way

00:32:39.010 --> 00:32:40.790
the Road Runner looks
at Wile E Coyote

00:32:40.790 --> 00:32:44.047
as he's charging off a cliff.

00:32:44.047 --> 00:32:46.380
I can still see the expression
on her face in my memory,

00:32:46.380 --> 00:32:48.800
because I can tell that
she had finally got me

00:32:48.800 --> 00:32:52.050
on board with what she
was trying to teach me,

00:32:52.050 --> 00:32:55.220
so she didn't want to
quash my enthusiasm.

00:32:55.220 --> 00:32:57.532
But at the same time,
there was no way

00:32:57.532 --> 00:32:59.740
I was going to sell a 20-book
series to any publisher

00:32:59.740 --> 00:33:01.270
anywhere.

00:33:01.270 --> 00:33:04.990
So she had to give me an
answer that would not dissuade

00:33:04.990 --> 00:33:07.050
me and not crush my enthusiasm.

00:33:07.050 --> 00:33:09.270
And so she just looks
at me and says, "Well, I

00:33:09.270 --> 00:33:11.790
think if you sell
a 20-book series,

00:33:11.790 --> 00:33:14.100
yeah-- you should
be doing fine."

00:33:14.100 --> 00:33:16.510
You know-- like that.

00:33:16.510 --> 00:33:19.290
So I had an idea
what I wanted to do,

00:33:19.290 --> 00:33:21.970
but I wasn't very good at
putting the story together

00:33:21.970 --> 00:33:24.560
and dropping things
out ahead of time.

00:33:24.560 --> 00:33:27.690
As I have continued
writing, I've

00:33:27.690 --> 00:33:29.640
learned to trust the
readers a whole lot more.

00:33:29.640 --> 00:33:30.709
Readers are smart.

00:33:30.709 --> 00:33:32.750
And so when I first started
setting up the story,

00:33:32.750 --> 00:33:34.610
I was only dropping one
or two little things

00:33:34.610 --> 00:33:37.320
in that were going to
come into in the long haul

00:33:37.320 --> 00:33:41.090
and otherwise trying to focus on
Harry's immediate surroundings,

00:33:41.090 --> 00:33:42.977
basically.

00:33:42.977 --> 00:33:44.310
Then I realized-- wait a minute.

00:33:44.310 --> 00:33:46.310
Readers are much better
at putting this together

00:33:46.310 --> 00:33:47.920
than I ever thought they were.

00:33:47.920 --> 00:33:50.130
So I started incorporating
more and more

00:33:50.130 --> 00:33:52.990
and being able to bring in more
subplots and more characters--

00:33:52.990 --> 00:33:57.100
more plans for the future,
more payoff from the past.

00:33:57.100 --> 00:34:00.900
Because I'm writing
for people like me.

00:34:00.900 --> 00:34:02.180
I'm writing for nerds.

00:34:02.180 --> 00:34:02.870
Nerds are smart.

00:34:02.870 --> 00:34:04.419
They can work this stuff out.

00:34:04.419 --> 00:34:05.960
So I sat down and
started doing that.

00:34:05.960 --> 00:34:08.120
And as I learned to
trust the audience more,

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:10.646
I think the books got better,
because the audience was

00:34:10.646 --> 00:34:12.770
able to grab them grab onto
them and enjoy it more.

