00:35:13.230 --> 00:35:15.230
AUDIENCE: What roleplaying
system are you using?

00:35:18.020 --> 00:35:19.520
How do your roleplaying
games differ

00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:22.380
from how your plots
ensue in a novel?

00:35:22.380 --> 00:35:25.688
And can I buy the Evil
Hat version of "Windlass"?

00:35:28.820 --> 00:35:31.400
JIM BUTCHER: We don't have
a deal with Evil Hat yet.

00:35:31.400 --> 00:35:33.774
I think they're trying to do
the Dresden collectible card

00:35:33.774 --> 00:35:36.280
game first.

00:35:36.280 --> 00:35:37.430
So there's that question.

00:35:37.430 --> 00:35:39.820
I'm answering in
reverse order here.

00:35:39.820 --> 00:35:44.540
How does my roleplaying
differ from my book writing?

00:35:44.540 --> 00:35:45.780
Not significantly.

00:35:45.780 --> 00:35:48.880
I tend to cliffhang
every play session, just

00:35:48.880 --> 00:35:51.750
like I do chapters, to
where the players are going,

00:35:51.750 --> 00:35:53.850
"We're going to stop there?"

00:35:53.850 --> 00:35:56.490
I like doing that.

00:35:56.490 --> 00:35:58.529
I like to torture the
players and to bring up

00:35:58.529 --> 00:36:00.820
the things that are just the
absolute wrong worst thing

00:36:00.820 --> 00:36:03.220
for them at the time.

00:36:03.220 --> 00:36:06.042
They like it.

00:36:06.042 --> 00:36:09.780
As far as game systems, I
ran the Cinder Spire stuff

00:36:09.780 --> 00:36:11.530
with Warhammer Fantasy Roleplay.

00:36:11.530 --> 00:36:15.110
Right now, I'm
playing Pathfinder,

00:36:15.110 --> 00:36:18.830
because I realized that my son
had reached 21 years of age

00:36:18.830 --> 00:36:20.789
and had never played
Dungeons &amp; Dragons.

00:36:20.789 --> 00:36:22.580
Every other roleplaying
game under the sun,

00:36:22.580 --> 00:36:25.390
but never D&amp;D. Except
I went out and got D&amp;D,

00:36:25.390 --> 00:36:28.000
and D&amp;D was fourth edition,
so it wasn't D&amp;D any more,

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:29.364
so I went got Pathfinder.

00:36:29.364 --> 00:36:31.530
And then I went and got the
Keep on the Borderlands,

00:36:31.530 --> 00:36:34.340
because that's where
you start playing D&amp;D.

00:36:34.340 --> 00:36:36.520
Only I set it during
a zombie apocalypse,

00:36:36.520 --> 00:36:40.049
so the keep on the borderlands
was the only human stronghold

00:36:40.049 --> 00:36:42.090
that was left, but in
order to be allowed inside,

00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:44.215
they had to agree to be on
the expeditionary force.

00:36:44.215 --> 00:36:46.920
And the expeditionary force got
sent off to the Caves of Chaos

00:36:46.920 --> 00:36:50.010
to see if they could make an
alliance with the greenskins

00:36:50.010 --> 00:36:51.220
against the zombies.

00:36:51.220 --> 00:36:53.930
So the Caves of Chaos as
a diplomatic mission--

00:36:53.930 --> 00:36:55.500
that was awesome.

00:36:55.500 --> 00:36:58.609
We had so much fun playing that.

00:36:58.609 --> 00:36:59.650
Whatever system comes by.

00:36:59.650 --> 00:37:01.710
I want to run something in fifth
edition now that it's come out.

00:37:01.710 --> 00:37:03.090
That looks pretty cool.

00:37:03.090 --> 00:37:04.080
You're very welcome.

00:37:04.080 --> 00:37:04.620
FEMALE SPEAKER:
When you play D&amp;D,

00:37:04.620 --> 00:37:06.610
do you DM, or do you
play as one of players?

00:37:06.610 --> 00:37:08.560
JIM BUTCHER: I mostly DM.

00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:11.200
When I play, I get so
bored with my character

00:37:11.200 --> 00:37:15.050
that I will either get heroic
or stupid about every two weeks

00:37:15.050 --> 00:37:17.680
so I can get a new character.

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:20.150
And at some point,
my GMs have just

00:37:20.150 --> 00:37:22.570
gone "Jim, just switch
to a different character,

00:37:22.570 --> 00:37:25.370
and we'll just pretend that this
guy hopped out of a backpack.

00:37:25.370 --> 00:37:25.870
OK?"

00:37:25.870 --> 00:37:27.320
FEMALE SPEAKER: It's magic!

00:37:27.320 --> 00:37:29.180
JIM BUTCHER: "That's
how it's going to be.

00:37:29.180 --> 00:37:32.570
Because you're really
stretching far to get

00:37:32.570 --> 00:37:41.480
killed at dinner in
the friendly convent."

00:37:41.480 --> 00:37:44.540
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much
for coming and speaking.

00:37:44.540 --> 00:37:48.300
One of Harry's caches, I guess,
in the beginning of the series

00:37:48.300 --> 00:37:51.734
is because of his magic, he
can't be anywhere near tech.

00:37:51.734 --> 00:37:52.900
He has to take cold showers.

00:37:52.900 --> 00:37:57.320
He basically lives this
aesthete life in a basement.

00:37:57.320 --> 00:38:00.950
As a writer, how does your
relationship with technology

00:38:00.950 --> 00:38:02.250
change the way that you write?

00:38:05.512 --> 00:38:07.720
JIM BUTCHER: How does my
relationship with technology

00:38:07.720 --> 00:38:10.150
change the way that I write?

00:38:10.150 --> 00:38:12.900
The biggest influence
that it's had on it

00:38:12.900 --> 00:38:16.800
is when I first started
writing the Dresden Files,

00:38:16.800 --> 00:38:20.320
I was a college student with no
money, so research for Chicago

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:23.860
was basically me buying a
couple of Chicago guidebooks

00:38:23.860 --> 00:38:26.680
and learning what I could
about Chicago from that.

00:38:26.680 --> 00:38:28.330
I didn't know anybody
who lived there.

00:38:28.330 --> 00:38:30.954
I didn't have enough
money to go there.

00:38:30.954 --> 00:38:32.620
So my research had
to come from whatever

00:38:32.620 --> 00:38:33.986
I could find in a book.

00:38:33.986 --> 00:38:35.860
Fast-forward a couple
years, and the Internet

00:38:35.860 --> 00:38:37.710
is up and running
on a regular basis

00:38:37.710 --> 00:38:39.780
that everybody can
get to, and people

00:38:39.780 --> 00:38:41.480
are able to take
digital pictures

00:38:41.480 --> 00:38:48.190
on their digital camera and then
upload them to the Internet.

00:38:48.190 --> 00:38:49.320
That was new.

00:38:49.320 --> 00:38:51.394
And so I would be
able to say to people

00:38:51.394 --> 00:38:53.060
who had read a couple
of my books, "Hey,

00:38:53.060 --> 00:38:55.070
I need to know what the east
wall of Graceland Cemetery

00:38:55.070 --> 00:38:55.760
looks like."

00:38:55.760 --> 00:38:58.000
And I would send that
out to this list of folks

00:38:58.000 --> 00:38:59.410
who lived in Chicago,
and I would get a reply--

00:38:59.410 --> 00:39:01.180
"I drive by there on the
way to work every morning.

00:39:01.180 --> 00:39:02.638
I'll take a picture
of it for you."

00:39:02.638 --> 00:39:05.835
And lo and behold-- by noon
I'd know what it looked like,

00:39:05.835 --> 00:39:06.710
and I could write it.

00:39:06.710 --> 00:39:07.860
That was amazing.

00:39:07.860 --> 00:39:12.840
And then later came you
guys-- came Google and Google

00:39:12.840 --> 00:39:15.260
Maps and Google Street View.

00:39:15.260 --> 00:39:18.130
So then I would go Google
Street View everything.

00:39:18.130 --> 00:39:21.100
I would use it and
set up my scenes

00:39:21.100 --> 00:39:24.650
by standing on the street
and looking around and being

00:39:24.650 --> 00:39:27.520
able to visually see everything
in the relationship of where

00:39:27.520 --> 00:39:29.770
all the objects were to
one another-- to the point

00:39:29.770 --> 00:39:33.830
that a couple years ago, I had
a Chicago SWAT captain come up

00:39:33.830 --> 00:39:36.490
to me and say, "You know
that scene you set up

00:39:36.490 --> 00:39:38.070
where you had the
shooter on the roof

00:39:38.070 --> 00:39:41.100
and he took out a
number of street lights

00:39:41.100 --> 00:39:46.190
so there was only one approach,
so that he could control

00:39:46.190 --> 00:39:47.220
this hostage situation?"

00:39:47.220 --> 00:39:47.803
I'm like yeah.

00:39:47.803 --> 00:39:49.870
He's like, "I
really need to know

00:39:49.870 --> 00:39:51.720
who you talked to
get that information,

00:39:51.720 --> 00:39:53.590
because we like to
keep track of people

00:39:53.590 --> 00:39:56.206
who know that kind of thing."

00:39:56.206 --> 00:39:57.580
And I had to look
at him and say,

00:39:57.580 --> 00:40:03.170
"I just used what I knew from
Call of Duty and Google Street

00:40:03.170 --> 00:40:04.220
View."

00:40:04.220 --> 00:40:08.290
And he just looks at me.

00:40:08.290 --> 00:40:11.582
I swear he aged five years,
just right during the time

00:40:11.582 --> 00:40:12.290
of that sentence.

00:40:12.290 --> 00:40:14.373
Then he shakes his head
and he's like, "Oh, man, I

00:40:14.373 --> 00:40:17.462
hate the Internet."

00:40:17.462 --> 00:40:19.670
But then there's all the
marketing aspects and so on,

00:40:19.670 --> 00:40:19.960
too.

00:40:19.960 --> 00:40:22.079
Because I can communicate
with my fans and readers

00:40:22.079 --> 00:40:22.620
all the time.

00:40:22.620 --> 00:40:24.340
I can get feedback
directly from them.

00:40:24.340 --> 00:40:28.150
All my beta reading
is on an email list

00:40:28.150 --> 00:40:29.860
that I sign people up for.

00:40:29.860 --> 00:40:31.480
I couldn't do it
without the Internet.

00:40:31.480 --> 00:40:35.520
And when I don't have the
Internet, I get twitchy.

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:39.130
That happens,
occasionally, and I scream.

00:40:39.130 --> 00:40:39.680
I run around.

00:40:39.680 --> 00:40:41.054
I don't know what
to do any more.

00:40:41.054 --> 00:40:42.192
I need my Internet.

00:40:42.192 --> 00:40:42.900
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:40:42.900 --> 00:40:44.710
JIM BUTCHER: You're
very welcome.

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:46.580
Hello!

00:40:46.580 --> 00:40:49.050
AUDIENCE: Generally, when
authors have their books turned

00:40:49.050 --> 00:40:51.580
into TV or movies, they're
given complete control

00:40:51.580 --> 00:40:55.200
over how to cash the
check, and that's it.

00:40:55.200 --> 00:40:58.530
I thought the Dresden
TV was done fairly well,

00:40:58.530 --> 00:41:00.084
given your restrictions.

00:41:00.084 --> 00:41:01.250
What did you think about it?

00:41:01.250 --> 00:41:02.416
What would you have changed?

00:41:02.416 --> 00:41:05.081
What might you do
differently if you could?

00:41:05.081 --> 00:41:07.580
JIM BUTCHER: I've always been
a glass-half-full kind of guy,

00:41:07.580 --> 00:41:13.440
so I like to think that the
TV series died before it could

00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:15.210
mess anything up too horribly.

00:41:15.210 --> 00:41:16.357
And so that's good.

00:41:16.357 --> 00:41:17.940
And it also introduced
a lot of people

00:41:17.940 --> 00:41:19.650
to the books, which
is also very good.

00:41:23.920 --> 00:41:26.049
Now, I think, if I
wanted to do it again--

00:41:26.049 --> 00:41:28.090
and it's a possibility
that it will happen again,

00:41:28.090 --> 00:41:32.000
because the rights are
out with a major company--

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.420
if it does happen
again, this time,

00:41:34.420 --> 00:41:37.540
I've attached myself to
the property in terms

00:41:37.540 --> 00:41:39.660
of I want to be a consultant.

00:41:39.660 --> 00:41:41.740
Not so that I can make it
exactly like my books--

00:41:41.740 --> 00:41:43.110
because I know it has
to change a bit when

00:41:43.110 --> 00:41:45.180
it goes to a different
medium-- but so that we

00:41:45.180 --> 00:41:49.616
can keep the same spirit of
awesome, the flavor of awesome

00:41:49.616 --> 00:41:50.990
that I like, in
the Dresden Files

00:41:50.990 --> 00:41:53.150
and to continue
using it elsewhere.

00:41:56.320 --> 00:42:00.850
All in all, I had no contractual
authority on my stuff, at all,

00:42:00.850 --> 00:42:01.720
when it went there.

00:42:01.720 --> 00:42:05.450
But I had friends on
the Internet and readers

00:42:05.450 --> 00:42:06.900
on the Internet
who worked out who

00:42:06.900 --> 00:42:08.830
was going to be in
charge of the project

00:42:08.830 --> 00:42:11.414
by putting together rumors and
then talked to me and said,

00:42:11.414 --> 00:42:13.580
"We think it's going to be
this guy-- Robert Wolfe."

00:42:13.580 --> 00:42:14.746
And I'm like, "Robert Wolfe?

00:42:14.746 --> 00:42:17.810
I loved the first couple seasons
of 'Andromeda.'" And so I

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:21.010
contacted Robert Wolfe and said
I suspect because of this fact

00:42:21.010 --> 00:42:22.490
and this fact that you're the
one who's going to be in charge

00:42:22.490 --> 00:42:22.700
of this.

00:42:22.700 --> 00:42:23.640
He's like, "That's amazing!

00:42:23.640 --> 00:42:25.098
You're like a
real-life detective!"

00:42:25.098 --> 00:42:28.192
And I'm like yes, I am.

00:42:28.192 --> 00:42:30.080
AUDIENCE: With magical powers!

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:32.680
JIM BUTCHER: It turns
out that he's a D&amp;D nerd,

00:42:32.680 --> 00:42:35.090
and we're both
Roman Empire buffs,

00:42:35.090 --> 00:42:37.730
so we sat down and
talked about it.

00:42:37.730 --> 00:42:40.030
And we got along really well.

00:42:40.030 --> 00:42:41.792
So I actually had a
lot more influence

00:42:41.792 --> 00:42:43.250
than you would
think over the show,

00:42:43.250 --> 00:42:45.910
because I got on so
well with Robert.

00:42:45.910 --> 00:42:47.390
I was very fortunate in that.

00:42:47.390 --> 00:42:50.710
But that was purely an
interpersonal thing.

00:42:50.710 --> 00:42:51.790
But he did a great job.

00:42:51.790 --> 00:42:52.340
I think you're right.

00:42:52.340 --> 00:42:54.298
I think he did a great
job with the limitations

00:42:54.298 --> 00:42:55.094
they were handed.

00:42:55.094 --> 00:42:55.760
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:42:55.760 --> 00:42:56.260
Thanks.

00:42:56.260 --> 00:42:58.630
JIM BUTCHER: Thank you.

00:42:58.630 --> 00:43:00.200
AUDIENCE: Sorry to
come back again.

00:43:00.200 --> 00:43:04.040
This is about Codex Alera.

00:43:04.040 --> 00:43:05.940
Those were a great
escape hatch for me

00:43:05.940 --> 00:43:07.550
one year, when it
was a bad year.

00:43:07.550 --> 00:43:09.290
JIM BUTCHER: Good.

00:43:09.290 --> 00:43:12.470
AUDIENCE: In those books, there
are two things that I noticed.

00:43:12.470 --> 00:43:14.260
The fight scenes
were incredible.

00:43:14.260 --> 00:43:18.870
I burned the edges of the pages
as I flipped them too quickly.

00:43:18.870 --> 00:43:21.200
I don't know if that
was part of what

00:43:21.200 --> 00:43:23.300
you wanted to do in
those books, to explore

00:43:23.300 --> 00:43:25.940
how to write a battle scene
in an engaging and really

00:43:25.940 --> 00:43:27.170
compelling way-- one.

00:43:27.170 --> 00:43:30.010
And, two, in Harry
Dresden and Codex Alera,

00:43:30.010 --> 00:43:33.700
you build these worlds and then,
to some extent-- no spoilers--

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:34.610
you destroy them.

00:43:34.610 --> 00:43:36.460
And what's that
like for a writer?

00:43:36.460 --> 00:43:36.780
JIM BUTCHER: I'm sorry.

00:43:36.780 --> 00:43:37.270
What was that?

00:43:37.270 --> 00:43:38.360
AUDIENCE: What's
that like for you?

00:43:38.360 --> 00:43:39.052
Is that funny?

00:43:41.314 --> 00:43:42.730
JIM BUTCHER: It's
like the guy who

00:43:42.730 --> 00:43:45.440
spends six months
building a model of Tokyo

00:43:45.440 --> 00:43:48.520
and then finally gets to
strap on a Godzilla suit.

00:43:48.520 --> 00:43:50.469
That's what it's like.

00:43:50.469 --> 00:43:52.760
You spend all this time
working and getting it perfect,

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:57.470
and then you get to look at it
and go, "And now-- mwahahahaha!

00:43:57.470 --> 00:43:59.840
I'm going to wipe out
everything in Dresden's life.

00:43:59.840 --> 00:44:01.535
I'm going to blow up his office.

00:44:01.535 --> 00:44:02.804
Kadoom!

00:44:02.804 --> 00:44:03.970
Going to burn down his home!

00:44:03.970 --> 00:44:04.690
Pew!

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:05.715
Smash his car!

00:44:05.715 --> 00:44:07.920
Kkkh!"

00:44:07.920 --> 00:44:10.564
It is so much fun to do that.

00:44:10.564 --> 00:44:11.980
AUDIENCE: I get
that sense that it

00:44:11.980 --> 00:44:13.910
would be fun to knock
over the sandcastle.

00:44:13.910 --> 00:44:15.170
JIM BUTCHER: It is!

00:44:15.170 --> 00:44:16.422
Oh, my god, it's awesome!

00:44:16.422 --> 00:44:17.630
AUDIENCE: I'm attached to it.

00:44:17.630 --> 00:44:19.745
I enjoy the destroy,
but I'm attached to it

00:44:19.745 --> 00:44:21.420
and now things are changing,
which is kind of the fun part.

00:44:21.420 --> 00:44:23.370
JIM BUTCHER: We can build
new stuff, you know?

00:44:23.370 --> 00:44:24.828
The great part
about being a writer

00:44:24.828 --> 00:44:27.990
is that it doesn't cost me any
more to destroy Chicago that it

00:44:27.990 --> 00:44:30.397
does to not destroy Chicago.

00:44:30.397 --> 00:44:32.730
I've got no budget that I
have to worry about with that.

00:44:32.730 --> 00:44:33.835
I just get words.

00:44:33.835 --> 00:44:36.460
I've got the ultimate freedom of
how I get to present the story

00:44:36.460 --> 00:44:39.461
or what I want to do.

00:44:39.461 --> 00:44:39.960
Yeah.

00:44:39.960 --> 00:44:42.560
It is tremendous fun, after you
spent all this time building

00:44:42.560 --> 00:44:45.830
things up, to go now I'm going
to turn everything on its side.

00:44:45.830 --> 00:44:47.730
It's like aha!

00:44:47.730 --> 00:44:49.780
I sometimes feel like one
of those painters that

00:44:49.780 --> 00:44:51.850
paints the giant
incomprehensible thing

00:44:51.850 --> 00:44:53.940
and then goes aha and
turns it upside-down,

00:44:53.940 --> 00:44:56.260
and it's a portrait of
one of the judges in the

00:44:56.260 --> 00:44:59.394
"Who's Got Talent" contest.

00:44:59.394 --> 00:45:00.560
Whose brain works like that?

00:45:00.560 --> 00:45:00.920
I don't know.

00:45:00.920 --> 00:45:01.545
That's amazing.

00:45:01.545 --> 00:45:03.910
But I sometimes get
to feel like that,

00:45:03.910 --> 00:45:05.930
where I get to
say now I've built

00:45:05.930 --> 00:45:08.880
all your expectations in this
one direction-- surprise.

00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:12.357
That's a ton of
fun-- totally worth

00:45:12.357 --> 00:45:13.440
the effort it takes to do.

00:45:15.939 --> 00:45:16.480
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:45:16.480 --> 00:45:17.188
JIM BUTCHER: Hey.

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:22.040
AUDIENCE: Back to the
roleplaying thing,

00:45:22.040 --> 00:45:24.800
as readers we love to see
our characters level up.

00:45:27.570 --> 00:45:32.840
But I've seen many authors
that level up too much.

00:45:32.840 --> 00:45:38.510
The campaign goes Monty Haul,
and it ceases to become fun,

00:45:38.510 --> 00:45:41.090
almost.

00:45:41.090 --> 00:45:43.670
In your books,
thankfully, you don't seem

00:45:43.670 --> 00:45:44.960
to have an issue with that.

00:45:44.960 --> 00:45:49.480
Is it hard not to write yourself
in a corner that way, though?

00:45:49.480 --> 00:45:50.400
JIM BUTCHER: No.

00:45:50.400 --> 00:45:54.631
Because I know what the end is.

00:45:54.631 --> 00:45:56.630
The reason that some of
the series go Monty Haul

00:45:56.630 --> 00:45:58.510
and go too long
and people just get

00:45:58.510 --> 00:46:01.852
too powerful-- they get
handed the dagger of Cain,

00:46:01.852 --> 00:46:04.060
or whatever, and it keeps
going and going and going--

00:46:04.060 --> 00:46:07.280
is that the story was
supposed to end before that,

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:09.390
and they did they
didn't end the story.

00:46:09.390 --> 00:46:11.954
Stories aren't stories unless
they have an ending to them.

00:46:11.954 --> 00:46:13.620
I'm one of the people
who believes that.

00:46:13.620 --> 00:46:17.460
I don't believe in a
never-ending story.

00:46:17.460 --> 00:46:21.380
For me, it's easy to keep
to keep Harry in check

00:46:21.380 --> 00:46:24.520
in terms of where he's getting
as he's getting more buff

00:46:24.520 --> 00:46:27.130
and getting more
contacts and so on,

00:46:27.130 --> 00:46:30.649
because I know what he's going
to be fighting in the next book

00:46:30.649 --> 00:46:32.440
and what's going to be
coming down the line

00:46:32.440 --> 00:46:34.800
and where he's going to wind up.

00:46:34.800 --> 00:46:37.460
Because I know all that
stuff, I can gauge-- OK, he

00:46:37.460 --> 00:46:38.600
needs to be about this far.

00:46:38.600 --> 00:46:40.016
Now he needs to
be about this far.

00:46:40.016 --> 00:46:42.000
No he needs to be
about this far.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:44.980
So that he is never the
super-overpowered guy

00:46:44.980 --> 00:46:46.950
who just smashes
everything all around him.

00:46:46.950 --> 00:46:50.190
He still remains the guy who is
not the big fish in the pond.

00:46:50.190 --> 00:46:51.740
He's the medium-sized
fish who needs

00:46:51.740 --> 00:46:57.860
to be smart and fast if he
wants to stay alive another day.

00:46:57.860 --> 00:47:00.290
Really, it's all about
pacing and knowing

00:47:00.290 --> 00:47:01.606
where you're going to wind up.

00:47:01.606 --> 00:47:02.980
I know where I'm
going to wind up

00:47:02.980 --> 00:47:05.800
and what he's going to be
doing when we get there,

00:47:05.800 --> 00:47:08.067
so it's easy to
keep him on track.

00:47:08.067 --> 00:47:09.400
AUDIENCE: Looking forward to it.

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:09.900
Thanks.

00:47:09.900 --> 00:47:12.180
JIM BUTCHER: Thank you.

00:47:12.180 --> 00:47:13.210
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:47:13.210 --> 00:47:14.702
You do action
really, really well.

00:47:14.702 --> 00:47:15.660
JIM BUTCHER: Thank you.

00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:16.060
AUDIENCE: I've always
wanted to know--

00:47:16.060 --> 00:47:17.850
have you studied martial arts?

00:47:17.850 --> 00:47:20.810
Do you have any black belts?

00:47:20.810 --> 00:47:22.922
How did you do the
research for that?

00:47:22.922 --> 00:47:25.880
Some of those moves
and some of what

00:47:25.880 --> 00:47:29.024
happens in combat you only
know if you've sparred before.

00:47:29.024 --> 00:47:31.190
JIM BUTCHER: I've got about
20 years of martial arts

00:47:31.190 --> 00:47:32.580
experience.

00:47:32.580 --> 00:47:34.290
I've studied a bunch
of different arts.

00:47:34.290 --> 00:47:36.120
I don't have black
belts in anything,

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:38.980
because I don't think
they're very important.

00:47:38.980 --> 00:47:41.430
But I like to go to new
schools, and when I come in,

00:47:41.430 --> 00:47:42.420
they're like well, do
you have any experience?

00:47:42.420 --> 00:47:44.560
And I'm like teach me like
I don't know anything,

00:47:44.560 --> 00:47:48.176
because I want to learn
what you have to teach me.

00:47:48.176 --> 00:47:50.550
Usually it doesn't take folks
very long to figure out oh,

00:47:50.550 --> 00:47:51.590
you've done some of this before.

00:47:51.590 --> 00:47:53.290
It's like well,
yeah, a little, but I

00:47:53.290 --> 00:47:54.540
want to learn what you've got.

00:47:56.920 --> 00:47:59.887
I started off in shorin
ryu at the local Y.

00:47:59.887 --> 00:48:01.470
And then I was very
fortunate to study

00:48:01.470 --> 00:48:02.940
ryukyu kempo for a long time.

00:48:02.940 --> 00:48:05.350
I actually got to spend
about three months

00:48:05.350 --> 00:48:08.500
in 90-minute one-on-one
lessons every day,

00:48:08.500 --> 00:48:12.090
because I was the only one who
ever came to the noon lesson.

00:48:12.090 --> 00:48:16.680
So I got noon lessons
with Mr. Shintaku, who

00:48:16.680 --> 00:48:20.010
was a 6-dan in
ryukyu kempo and was

00:48:20.010 --> 00:48:23.910
a Japanese collegiate
aikido champion

00:48:23.910 --> 00:48:26.420
and was a really good
teacher-- who would hurt you

00:48:26.420 --> 00:48:29.440
if you did it wrong.

00:48:29.440 --> 00:48:31.690
When you're in that one-on-one
circumstance like that,

00:48:31.690 --> 00:48:32.760
you learn very rapidly.

00:48:32.760 --> 00:48:35.020
You learn a lot very fast.

00:48:35.020 --> 00:48:37.180
He was the reason I've
got one good martial arts

00:48:37.180 --> 00:48:40.480
story-- that's my own, I mean.

00:48:40.480 --> 00:48:46.090
After that, in college, it was
goja shoryu, aikido, kung-fu,

00:48:46.090 --> 00:48:48.805
some jiu jitsu, some wing chun.

00:48:48.805 --> 00:48:51.180
I wasn't very good at aikido,
but it was a beautiful art.

00:48:51.180 --> 00:48:53.725
I'm too impatient to
be good at aikido.

00:48:53.725 --> 00:48:55.170
Aikido is one of
those arts that's

00:48:55.170 --> 00:48:57.530
basically like how foolish
would you like to look?

00:48:57.530 --> 00:48:58.630
Come at me that hard.

00:49:01.240 --> 00:49:05.670
I've done some kung-fu, some
taekwondo, some wing chun.

00:49:05.670 --> 00:49:09.150
Epee, foil, saber.

00:49:09.150 --> 00:49:10.570
I've got some weapon forms in.

00:49:13.330 --> 00:49:15.000
But I'm kind of a dilettante.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:17.370
I can handle myself reasonably
well against somebody

00:49:17.370 --> 00:49:18.932
who is not a professional.

00:49:18.932 --> 00:49:21.140
A professional would eat me
up, because professionals

00:49:21.140 --> 00:49:23.014
are completely different
than everybody else.

00:49:25.489 --> 00:49:26.530
But I have learned a lot.

00:49:26.530 --> 00:49:28.140
And I've got to
talk to people a lot

00:49:28.140 --> 00:49:32.260
and borrow stories from them.

00:49:32.260 --> 00:49:36.990
Just generally, I've had
a lot of fun doing it.

00:49:36.990 --> 00:49:39.280
What I realized at some
point-- I don't know,

00:49:39.280 --> 00:49:41.100
maybe 10 years in--
I looked around

00:49:41.100 --> 00:49:43.220
and I realized wait
a minute, the ability

00:49:43.220 --> 00:49:45.980
to disassemble another human
being with your bare hands

00:49:45.980 --> 00:49:48.970
is not really useful
on a day-to-day basis.

00:49:48.970 --> 00:49:50.500
It doesn't really
help you out when

00:49:50.500 --> 00:49:53.107
you're in the grocery store.

00:49:53.107 --> 00:49:55.690
But other lessons from martial
arts, especially about balance,

00:49:55.690 --> 00:49:57.064
teach you a whole
lot that's very

00:49:57.064 --> 00:49:58.634
good for the rest of your life.

00:49:58.634 --> 00:49:59.565
AUDIENCE: That's true.

00:49:59.565 --> 00:50:00.065
Cool.

00:50:04.471 --> 00:50:06.220
AUDIENCE: Maybe this
is an unfair question

00:50:06.220 --> 00:50:09.200
but if you weren't a writer--
if it didn't take off the way

00:50:09.200 --> 00:50:12.760
it did-- where do you think
your life would have gone?

00:50:12.760 --> 00:50:17.140
My last real paying job, I
was working technical support

00:50:17.140 --> 00:50:19.100
at a local Internet provider.

00:50:19.100 --> 00:50:20.790
I was the guy who
came in at 10:00

00:50:20.790 --> 00:50:24.740
and was responsible for the
entire place until 6:00 AM.

00:50:24.740 --> 00:50:27.560
And it was the largest
provider in Oklahoma.

00:50:27.560 --> 00:50:31.120
It provided for
everybody at that time.

00:50:31.120 --> 00:50:35.060
They even had more customers
than AOL did in Oklahoma.

00:50:35.060 --> 00:50:35.879
It was a great job.

00:50:35.879 --> 00:50:36.670
I had a great boss.

00:50:36.670 --> 00:50:38.860
It was my Fezziwig job.

00:50:38.860 --> 00:50:40.190
My boss was former military.

00:50:40.190 --> 00:50:43.020
He offered to fight a guy for
me once-- that's how good a boss

00:50:43.020 --> 00:50:43.780
he was.

00:50:43.780 --> 00:50:46.970
I had a guy who was on the phone
when my boss came in at 6:00,

00:50:46.970 --> 00:50:50.910
and he had messed up his
computer by around 8:00

00:50:50.910 --> 00:50:52.640
the previous night,
and then he'd

00:50:52.640 --> 00:50:55.100
to fix it until 4:00 in the
morning, when he finally called

00:50:55.100 --> 00:50:57.540
me-- at which point there
wasn't a whole lot I could do,

00:50:57.540 --> 00:51:00.570
because he had
mangled it so badly.

00:51:00.570 --> 00:51:03.457
He was screaming at me on the
phone when the boss walks in.

00:51:03.457 --> 00:51:05.040
My boss actually
offered to fight him.

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:05.930
He was ex-military.

00:51:05.930 --> 00:51:08.090
He was about
six-two, about 245--

00:51:08.090 --> 00:51:10.810
played basketball with all
the college intern guys.

00:51:10.810 --> 00:51:12.720
Had this buzz cut,
blue eyes-- looked

00:51:12.720 --> 00:51:15.545
like the reincarnation of Thor.

00:51:15.545 --> 00:51:17.170
He was like yeah,
I'll be happy to talk

00:51:17.170 --> 00:51:19.702
to you about my employee.

00:51:19.702 --> 00:51:21.160
If you're that
upset, come on down,

00:51:21.160 --> 00:51:22.909
and I'll be the one
that you'll deal with.

00:51:22.909 --> 00:51:25.650
I was like OK, man, when you
call me in on a Saturday,

00:51:25.650 --> 00:51:27.590
I'm coming in after this.

00:51:27.590 --> 00:51:31.110
They liked me because I had
just enough ability at code

00:51:31.110 --> 00:51:34.131
that I could kludge something
together until morning

00:51:34.131 --> 00:51:36.130
so that I didn't have to
go get a programmer out

00:51:36.130 --> 00:51:36.985
of bed at 3:00.

00:51:39.314 --> 00:51:41.730
I would wait until 6:00, and
then when I was off my shift,

00:51:41.730 --> 00:51:43.660
I would give him a call,
because that was when, I knew,

00:51:43.660 --> 00:51:44.590
his alarm went off.

00:51:44.590 --> 00:51:45.810
He's like is there a problem?

00:51:45.810 --> 00:51:46.860
Yeah there's a problem.

00:51:46.860 --> 00:51:49.720
There's a patch program
that's kind of running,

00:51:49.720 --> 00:51:51.220
and it's sort of
making things work,

00:51:51.220 --> 00:51:53.366
but maybe you should get
in as quick as you can.

00:51:53.366 --> 00:51:55.240
He's like OK, thank you
for not waking me up.

00:51:55.240 --> 00:51:56.540
And I loved that
job, because I liked

00:51:56.540 --> 00:51:57.789
helping people over the phone.

00:51:57.789 --> 00:52:00.410
I liked getting them back
onto their video games.

00:52:00.410 --> 00:52:02.870
I liked solving problems.

00:52:02.870 --> 00:52:03.835
That was fun.

00:52:03.835 --> 00:52:05.710
Plus, there was a lot
of "EverQuest" going on

00:52:05.710 --> 00:52:08.166
at that job.

00:52:08.166 --> 00:52:10.540
Come to think of it, I actually
wrote the first two books

00:52:10.540 --> 00:52:12.780
of the Dresden Files and
the first Codex Alera book

00:52:12.780 --> 00:52:15.529
on that job.

00:52:15.529 --> 00:52:16.070
There you go.

00:52:16.070 --> 00:52:18.110
I would probably be doing
something in that area

00:52:18.110 --> 00:52:21.630
still, because I love my tech.

00:52:21.630 --> 00:52:23.850
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Last two questions.

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:26.160
AUDIENCE: Silly
Dresden Files question.

00:52:26.160 --> 00:52:31.150
Remember from "Cold Days"
the shenanigans regarding

00:52:31.150 --> 00:52:32.355
the origin of the keep?

00:52:35.860 --> 00:52:40.220
Can we expect more time
shenanigans in future books?

00:52:40.220 --> 00:52:41.890
JIM BUTCHER: More
time shenanigans?

00:52:41.890 --> 00:52:42.390
Sir?

00:52:42.390 --> 00:52:46.220
One of the laws of magic states
that you cannot mess with time

00:52:46.220 --> 00:52:46.950
like that!

00:52:46.950 --> 00:52:50.870
Of course there will be
more time shenanigans!

00:52:50.870 --> 00:52:53.190
I only established the
seven laws of magic

00:52:53.190 --> 00:52:55.180
so that I could have
Dresden methodically break

00:52:55.180 --> 00:52:56.171
them one by one!

00:52:58.710 --> 00:53:01.710
AUDIENCE: All right, speaking of
silly questions-- after the way

00:53:01.710 --> 00:53:04.770
you dealt with Cat Sith
in the Dresden books

00:53:04.770 --> 00:53:08.030
and having a whole
race of talking cats,

00:53:08.030 --> 00:53:09.130
I'm kind of scared.

00:53:09.130 --> 00:53:09.810
Should I be?

00:53:12.202 --> 00:53:13.410
JIM BUTCHER: It's not so bad.

00:53:13.410 --> 00:53:19.910
They're like fuzzy, really,
really, really egotistical

00:53:19.910 --> 00:53:21.290
little libertarians.

00:53:21.290 --> 00:53:23.840
They're rolling all
over everywhere.

00:53:23.840 --> 00:53:25.340
They're completely independent.

00:53:25.340 --> 00:53:27.380
They don't want to pitch
in to anybody's help.

00:53:27.380 --> 00:53:28.320
They're arrogant.

00:53:28.320 --> 00:53:29.690
They're egotistical.

00:53:29.690 --> 00:53:30.710
They're close-minded.

00:53:30.710 --> 00:53:32.090
They're adorable.

00:53:32.090 --> 00:53:33.150
They get away with it.

00:53:33.150 --> 00:53:35.990
And they're almost as good
as they think they are,

00:53:35.990 --> 00:53:40.220
which makes them very
useful to the team.

00:53:40.220 --> 00:53:43.270
At the same time, the
cats in these stories,

00:53:43.270 --> 00:53:45.754
